SIMPLE: handful
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: handful
<hw>hand"ful</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧nd"f⟦usdot⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>handfuls</plw>
<pr>(h⟦acr⟧nd"f⟦usdot⟧lz)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[AS.
<ets>handfull</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>As much as the hand will
grasp or contain.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hand's breadth; four inches.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Knap the tongs together about a <qex>handful</qex> from the
bottom.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small quantity or number.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>handful</qex> of men were tied to very hard duty.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person, task, or situation, which is the most that
one can manage; <as>as, my two-year-old is a
<ex>handful</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To have one's handful</b></col>, <cd>to have one's hands
full; to have all one can do.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>had their handful</qex> to defend themselves from
firing.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hand-hole</ent>⟦br⟧
